{{Infobox power transmission line | name = Nkenda–Mpondwe–Beni High Voltage Power Line | photo = | caption = | map = | country = [[Uganda]] & [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] | state = | province = | coordinates ={{coord|00|03|12|N|29|43|26|E|type:landmark_region:UG|display=inline}} | direction = East to West | start = Nkenda, [[Uganda]] | through = [[Mpondwe]], [[Kasindi]] | finish = [[Beni, Democratic Republic of the Congo|Beni]], [[DR Congo]] | par = | owner = [[Government of Uganda]] & [[Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]] | partners = [[Nile Basin Initiative|NELSAP]] & [[African Development Bank]] | operator = [[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] & Congolese Electricity Utility Company | cable_manufacturer = | cable_installer = | cable_layer = | substation_manufacturer = | substation_installer = | contractors = | construction = TBD | expected = TBD | est = | decom = | type = | current_type = AC | length =153 | length_mi = | tower_no = | capacity = | AC_voltage = 220kV | DC_voltage = | poles_no = | circuits_no = 2 }}
The '''Nkenda–Mpondwe–Beni High Voltage Power Line''' is a proposed [[high voltage]] electricity power line, connecting the high voltage [[Electrical substation| substation]] at [[Nkenda]], in [[Kasese District]], in the [[Western Region, Uganda|Western Region]] of [[Uganda]], to another high voltage substation at [[Beni, Democratic Republic of the Congo|Beni]], in [[North Kivu Province]], in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref name="One">{{cite web| date=3 January 2018 |format=PDF | |url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/digital_assets/a1cd019e-418b-4297-8260-ba308df58da0/32-ERA-Full-pg.pdf |accessdate=3 January 2018 |author=ERA | publisher=[[Electricity Regulatory Authority]] (ERA) | location=Kampala | title=Regional Power Transmission Projects}}</ref>
==Location== The 220kV power line, begins at the substation at [[Nkenda]], in Kasese District, Western Uganda. The line travels in a south-westerly direction through [[Mpondwe]], to [[Kasindi]], in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]. There, it takes a general north-westerly course, to end at [[Beni, Democratic Republic of the Congo|Beni]], North Kivu Province, in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]. The distance traveled by this power line in Uganda is approximately {{convert|73|km|0}}.<ref name="Two">{{cite web| url=http://www.uetcl.com/index.php/site-administrator/projects-at-feasibility-study |title=Projects At Feasibility Study Level |last=UETCL | publisher=[[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] (UETCL) | date=May 2016 |accessdate=3 July 2017 |location=Kampala}}</ref> The line travels approximately {{convert|80|km|0}}, in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.<ref name="Three">{{cite web| accessdate=3 January 2018 | url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Congo_(Kinshasa)_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Kasindi%2C%20North-Kivu%2C%20Democratic%20Republic%20of%20the%20Congo&toplace=Beni%2C%20North-Kivu%2C%20Democratic%20Republic%20of%20the%20Congo&dt1=ChIJOWBBpzjZYRcRa_fNngjg0lc&dt2=ChIJF7pReQGrYRcRPKWy9tFHUqQ |title=Distance between Kasindi, North-Kivu, Democratic Republic of the Congo and Beni, North-Kivu, Democratic Republic of the Congo | date=3 January 2018 |last=Globefeed.com |publisher=Globefeed.com}}</ref>
==Overview== This power line is planned to transmit electricity to the eastern parts of the Democratic Republic of the Congo, as part the regional power-sharing protocols of the [[Nile Basin Initiative|Nile Equatorial Lakes Subsidiary Action Program]]. Uganda plans to sell electricity to neighboring countries, including the Democratic Republic of the Congo, after [[Karuma Hydroelectric Power Station]] and [[Isimba Hydroelectric Power Station]] become operational in 2019.<ref name="Four">{{cite web| accessdate=3 January 2018 |first=Elias |last=Biryabarema |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N1L22NB | title=Uganda says signs deal with Congo to build $150 million power line | date=16 August 2017 | publisher=[[Reuters.com]]}}</ref><ref name="Five">{{cite web|url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Uganda-to-export-electricity-to-South-Sudan--DR-Congo/688334-4123918-np6qx4z/index.html |title=Uganda to export electricity to South Sudan, DR Congo |location=Kampala |date=4 October 2017 | accessdate=3 January 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |last=Stephen Otage | first=and Nelson Wesonga}}</ref> The government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo has plans to extend the high-voltage power line to [[Bunia]] and [[Butebo]].<ref name="Four"/>
==Construction== The two governments are in discussions on how to fund the construction of the power line, using loans from the [[African Development Bank]], with each country being responsible for the portion of the line in her territory.<ref name="Four"/>
